                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1863" notAfter="1867"><p>Probably rebound in a hybrid British-Indian style in the <placeName cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535">Delhi</placeName> for former owner <persName key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">George William Hamilton</persName>.</p>
                        <p>Resewn at two unsupported stations. Endpapers of comparatively thin, bright ivoury-coloured wove paper, likely machine-made in the <placeName cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7008653">Britain</placeName>added at front and back, then the edges , and twined chevron endbands worked over round cores at head and tail  
                           Covered in full brownish-red goatskin <material>leather</material> over pasteboards, with squares at the edges and defined joints, but without a flap (Type III binding per Déroche).</p>
                        <decoNote type="binding">Boards magins and spine dyed brown ~ 13 mm in from the edges, with strips of bright green paper strips applied to the interior edges, then repeatedly tooled with insular dots. 
                           Margins ruled in yellow single lines, with double lines along the perimeters. 
                           The same features appear on <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7070"><idno>Persian MS 572</idno></ref> and <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7133"><idno>631</idno></ref>. A handritten octagonal label bears the title on the spine, with another horizontal rectangle bearing the same applied to the exterior left cover.</decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                           <height>254</height>
                           <width>156</width>
                           <depth>26</depth>
                        </dimensions></p> 
                        <condition>Handle binding with caution. In fair condition with exteriors and board edges abraded bowing.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>Three dates given: <origDate calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1854">1270 AH</origDate>
                  <origDate calendar="#Hindu" when="1854">Samvat 1911 (1854 CE)</origDate></origin>
                  <provenance><p>
                     Subsequently acquired by <persName type="supplied" key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William Hamilton (1807-1868)</persName> 
                     who served in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">India</placeName> <date calendar="#Gregorian" from="1823" to="1867">from 1823 to 1867</date>, latterly as Commissioner in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535" key="place_7001535">Delhi</placeName>. 
                     He acquired over a thousand Indian and Persian manuscripts, from which the
                     <orgName type="standard" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/134857252">British Museum</orgName> selected 352, now held in the
                     <orgName type="standard" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/121814978">British Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </provenance> 
                  <provenance>
                     <persName type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058">
                        Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName> purchased  the remainder of Hamilton's collection in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1868">1868</date>.
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr" key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup"
                     >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                        when="1901">1901</date> from <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
